ce:section.ce:para:
Carbon dots (CDs) or quantum dots (QDs) are zero-dimensional (OD) carbon based nanomaterials with a size below 20 nm [1–3]. CDs are new rising stars in the carbon family and have withdrawn significant awareness because of their various properties including extremely high and harmonize photoluminescence (PL), small size, high quantum yield, substantial biocompatibility, low toxicity, magnified adsorption ability, cost-effectivity, eco-friendliness, excellent electric conductivity, high solubility and excellent stability [1–3]. CDs are extensively employed for various industrial and biological applications such as in catalysis, biomedicine, sensors, energy storage, optoelectronics, anticounterfeiting, and recently as corrosion inhibitors (Fig. 1
                     ) [4,5]. Noticeably, recently industrial and biological applications of existing carbon allotropes are limited because of their difficult and expensive synthesis and isolation. Carbon nanotubes (CNTs), graphene (G) and fullerene have poor solubility in polar solutions that significantly confines their application [6,7]. Unlikely, CDs exhibit excellent solubility and anticorrosive activities. CDs can be synthesized using various protocols reported in literature and their characterization is mainly achieved by different spectral analyses including TEM, UV–vis, Raman, FT-IR, XRD, EDX and XPS techniques [8–10]. Some important carbon allotropes with their dimensional specification are illustrated in Fig. 2

                     [11]. Physiochemical properties of CDs including corrosion inhibition potential can be suitably modified by doping them with S, N, B and P heteroatoms [12–14]. Literature study suggests that CDs with and without doping are extensively employed as aqueous phase corrosion inhibitors for different metal-electrolyte systems. Because of their nanomeric nature, CDs are associated with excellent surface coverage and anticorrosive activity.
